  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-lilac-900)]" flip />

  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming and Heat: Spitz Coat Rules at Half Scale" imageAlt="Pomsky puppy having its double coat brushed" imageSrc={imgScene4} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Two double-coated parents means the coat contract arrives regardless of which size the lottery dealt: brushing 3 to 4 times a week to the skin, daily through the seasonal blows, thorough drying after rain, and never shaving, the maintained double coat insulates against our heat, a shaved one wrecks the system.</p>
      <p>The heat rules are the standard spitz set: exercise before 9am or after 6pm, ventilated or air-conditioned afternoons, water everywhere. Smaller Pomskies carry the heat more easily than their full-Husky parent, but the physiology is the same family, so the habits are too.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Pomsky Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Pomsky puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene5} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Pomsky goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The health picture draws from both sides of the family: patellar luxation from the Pomeranian branch, worth the standard small-dog kneecap awareness; eye checks from the Husky branch, where juvenile cataracts run in some lines; and dental care scaled to whichever jaw size the lottery produced, starting day one either way.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week; portions track the adult size as it reveals itself. See the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Pomsky's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Pomsky puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene6} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Pomsky explores the room, the escape audit is done together, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and structured. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short play bursts; the spitz spark shows early, so channel it gently from the start.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and possibly the first tiny howl debuts. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; early voice and leash work pays off for fifteen years. See what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

  <div id="reviews" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <Carousel
      heading="What Curious Tails Owners Say"
